definition.value: A group which advocates for LGBTQIA+ persons.
An organization which publishes or reviews some form of media, typically newsmedia.
Organizations which analyze media in some capacity, such as for fact checking.
Organizations which monitor media for particular attributes or overly suitability for a general audience or for specific audiences.
Professional associations formed of and for pediatricians.
A medical institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
A pediatric medical institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.

A hate group is a social group that advocates and practices hatred, hostility, or violence towards members of a race, ethnicity, nation, religion, gender, gender identity, sexual orientation or any other designated sector of society.
Hate groups who direct their hatred primarily against LGBTQIA+ people.
Hate groups who direct their hatred primarily against gay people, particularly gay men.
Hate groups who direct their hatred primarily against lesbians.
Hate groups who direct their hatred primarily against bisexual people.
Hate groups who direct their hatred primarily against transgender people.
A group that advocates for transgender people.
Social groups as represented on the internet, usually on the World Wide Web.
An internet group on the social media platform Facebook.
Facebook groups related to the LGBTQIA+ community or any of its various subcommunities.
Facebook groups related to the transgender community or any of its various subcommunities.
Efforts and techniques utilized in order to prevent sexual assault and rape from occurring.
A statement intended to demean and brutalize another, or the use of cruel and derogatory language on the basis of real or alleged membership in a social group.
Despite the name, not all hate speech is speech and many forms of hate speech do not include any kind of verbal communication.
Hate speech which takes place online (e.g. the internet, social media platforms).
Nonverbal communication in which space plays a role; also includes behavior influenced by population density (i.e. behavior in tight spaces versus open spaces).
Nonverbal communication in which body movement plays a large role.
Nonverbal communication in which interactions happen via the sense of touch.
Nonverbal communication in which time plays a role.
Types of meta-communication which may modify meaning, give nuanced meaning, or convey emotion such as using prosody, pitch, volume, and intonation.
The touch or pressing of one's lips against another person or an object.

Note that the cultural connotations of kissing vary widely. Depending on the culture and context, a kiss can express sentiments of love, passion, romance, sexual attraction, sexual activity, sexual arousal, affection, respect, greeting, friendship, peace, and good luck, among many others. In some situations, a kiss is a ritual, formal or symbolic gesture indicating devotion, respect, or sacrament.
A kiss which indicates romantic and/or sexual feeling.
Different types of kissing, categorized by the social function the kiss fulfills.
Different types of kisses organized by the anatomical structure received by the lips (i.e. lip-to-lip kissing, lip-to-hand kissing, etc.
A kiss in which a person's lips contact another person's cheek.
A kiss in which a person's lips contact another person's nose.
A kiss in which a person's lips contact another person's lips.
A kiss in which a person's lips contact another person's hand or hands.
An act, usually of endearment, in which two or more people put their arms around the neck, back, or waist of one another and hold each other closely.
A hug involving more than two persons.
A kiss in which a person's lips contact another person's forehead.
A kiss which is part of some ritual, religious or otherwise.
A kiss indicating peace or transmitting a feeling of peace as part of a ritual.
This term is almost exclusively used to refer to an expression of spiritual devotion used in the early days of the Christian Church.
A kiss given out of reverence or respect to another person or thing.
An amorous kiss in which the participants' tongues extend to touch each other's lips or tongue.
A kiss in which there is tongue contact.
The act of touching a part of a body in a way that causes involuntary twitching movements or laughter.
A kiss used as a salutation between friends or acquaintances.

Gesturing is a form of nonverbal communication in which visible bodily actions communicate particular messages, either in place of speech or together and in parallel with spoken words. Gestures include movement of the hands, face, or other parts of the body.
A month dedicated to bringing awareness to a certain cause and/or condition.
A day dedicated to bringing awareness to a certain civil cause and/or condition.
A group which advocates against sexual assault.
An anatomical point that is part of the vagina.
A theoretical erogenous area of the vagina that, when stimulated, may lead to strong sexual arousal, powerful orgasms and potential vaginal ejaculation.

Note that the existence of the G-spot has not been proven with scientific evidence. Some have theorized that it may in fact be an extension of the clitoris, which together may be the cause of orgasms experienced vaginally.
